{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}} {{Use British English|date=June 2016}} {{Infobox television | show_name = A Short Stay in Switzerland | image = | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = | genre = | creator = | based_on = | writer = | screenplay = | story = | director = [[Simon Curtis (filmmaker)|Simon Curtis]] | starring = | narrated = | theme_music_composer = | country = United Kingdom | language = English | num_episodes = | producer = | editor = | cinematography = | runtime = 90 minutes | company = | distributor = | budget = | network = | first_aired = {{Film date|df=y|TV=y|2009|1|25}} | last_aired = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | website = }} '''''A Short Stay in Switzerland''''' is a 2009 British television film directed by [[Simon Curtis (filmmaker)|Simon Curtis]] and written by [[Frank McGuinness]]. It stars [[Julie Walters]], who won the [[International Emmy Award]] for Best Actress for her performance as Dr Anne Turner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/a-short-stay-in-switzerland-v534879|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120719045746/http://www.allmovie.com/movie/a-short-stay-in-switzerland-v534879|deadurl=yes|title=A Short Stay in Switzerland - Trailers, Reviews, Synopsis, Showtimes …|date=19 July 2012|archivedate=19 July 2012|website=Archive.is|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author= |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/6641279/Julie-Walters-stars-as-Britons-dominate-International-Emmys.html |title=Julie Walters stars as Britons dominate International Emmys |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=2009-11-24 |accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref> It was produced by [[BBC]].
It was also nominated for other numerous awards including the [[BAFTA Award]] for Best Single TV Drama and Best Actress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1273813/awards|title=A Short Stay in Switzerland (2009 TV Movie) : Awards|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref>
==Plot== Having recently witnessed the death of her husband from a neurological disease, Dr. Anne Turner is diagnosed with a near-identical illness and determines to end her life once her condition has reached a critical point. As her health deteriorates, Anne's son and two daughters struggle to reach a consensus over their mother's intentions and while they search for alternative options, silent recriminations and stubborn practicality threaten to tear the family apart. With her family at logger heads, Anne must also face the fury of her best friend, whose opposing views bring them into direct conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00h62w9|title=A Short Stay in Switzerland - BBC One|website=BBC|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref>
==Cast== * [[Julie Walters]] as Dr Anne Turner * [[Stephen Campbell Moore]] as Edward * [[Lyndsey Marshal]] as Jessica * [[Liz White (actress)|Liz White]] as Sophie * [[Michelle Fairley]] as Mrs Savery * [[Will Knightley]] as Dr Jack Turner * [[Patrick Malahide]] as Richard * [[Harriet Walter]] as Clare<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ezD0GddG1yM|title=YouTube|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref>
==Background== The film was inspired by the true story of Dr. Anne Turner (25 January 1939 - 24 January 2006), who took her own life in a Zurich clinic having developed the incurable neurodegenerative disease [[Progressive supranuclear palsy|progressive supranuclear palsy (PSP)]]. Before being diagnosed with PSP, Dr. Turner had nursed her husband until he died from a similar disease, [[Multiple system atrophy|multiple system atrophy (MSA)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2006/jan/25/health.medicineandhealth|title='I believe I must end my life while I am still able'|first1=Sarah|last1=Boseley|first2=Clare|last2=Dyer|date=25 January 2006|accessdate=13 January 2018|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref> Her brother also was victim of a progressive condition, [[Motor neurone disease|motor neurone disease]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/4625538.stm|title=Clinic assists doctor's suicide|date=13 January 2018|accessdate=13 January 2018|website=News.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>
