{{Okinawan name|Tomigusuku}}
{{nihongo|'''Tomigusuku ''[[Ueekata]]'' Seiryō'''|豊見城 親方 盛良|extra=1 July 1586 &ndash; 26 September 1642}}, also known by his Chinese style name {{nihongo|'''Mō Taiun'''|毛 泰運}}, was a bureaucrat of the [[Ryukyu Kingdom]].<ref name=jiten>"[http://ryukyushimpo.jp/okinawa-dic/prentry-42325.html Tomigusuku Seiryō]." ''Okinawa konpakuto jiten'' (沖縄コンパクト事典, "Okinawa Compact Encyclopedia").</ref>

Tomigusuku Seiryō was the sixth head of an aristocrat family called [[Mō-shi Tomigusuku Dunchi]] ({{lang|ja|毛氏豊見城殿内}}). He was the eldest son of [[Tomigusuku Seizoku]].<ref name=jiten/>

Tomigusuku was elected as a member of ''[[Sanshikan]]'' in 1627.<ref name=jiten/><ref>[http://manwe.lib.u-ryukyu.ac.jp/d-archive/s/viewer?&cd=00030240 中山王府相卿伝職年譜　向祐等著写本]</ref> King [[Shō Hō]] dispatched Prince [[Chatan Chōshū]] ({{lang|ja|北谷 朝秀}}, also known as Shō Kei {{lang|ja|尚 慶}}) and him in 1638 to celebrate [[Shimazu Mitsuhisa]] succeeded as ''[[daimyō]]'' of [[Satsuma Domain|Satsuma]]. Prince Chatan returned to Ryukyu in the next year, but Tomigusuku remained in Satsuma to handle official business. He sailed back to Ryukyu in 1642 but his ship was shipwrecked near [[Tokunoshima]].<ref name=jiten/><ref>''[[Chūzan Seifu]]'', appendix vol.1</ref> His body was not found so he had no grave.<ref>http://syuri-sinkoukai.com/13daigaku.html</ref>

